		<div class="right"><a href="index.html"><img src="../sle.png" alt="SLE 2012"></a><br><code>sle2012/paper16</code></div>
			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2012</a> paper:</span><br><i>A Common Foundational Theory for Bridging Two Levels in Ontology-Driven Conceptual Modeling</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/GiancarloGuizzardi.html">Giancarlo Guizzardi</a>, <a href="../profile/VeruskaZamborlini.html">Veruska Zamborlini</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-642-36089-3_17">10.1007/978-3-642-36089-3_17</a></li>
<li>Original shorter version of <a href="../sle2012s/paper02.html"><em>Using a trope-based foundational ontology for bridging different areas of concern in ontology-driven conceptual modeling</em></a> (SLE 2012 SI)</li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3e.html"><span class="tagM">T3E: Ontologies</span></a><ul><li> The paper is centered on foundational ontologies and ontology-driven conceptual modeling (e.g., OntoUML, OWL).
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1a.html"><span class="tagL">T1A: Design</span></a><ul><li> It (re)designs a set of modeling primitives/guidelines grounded in an ontological theory, which is essentially language design work.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4b.html"><span class="tagL">T4B: Horizontal Transformation</span></a><ul><li> A key part is mapping conceptual models to computational codification languages (e.g., OWL), i.e., cross-language conversion.
</li></ul></li></ul>
